Menu

The Tinellbian Languages Dictionary

  • Random Entry

About

This dictionary aims to describe all the vocabulary items of the twenty Tinellbian languages, consisting of High Lulani and its descendants. In addition, miscellaneous English neologisms have been added, including proper nouns.

Searching

The search box at the bottom of each page allows one to proceed directly to any dictionary entry. Contrariwise, the search box in the navigation pane runs a general search of the site.

-a

High Lulani

、あ

/ə/

derivational suffix ( noun / verb → interjection )

interjection marker; inj

Examples

  • mica みや hello
  • hacca はっや good morning
  • nara なら good night
  • hira ひら please
  • kica きや pardon?

-’a

See also: ’a

High Lulani

あ

/ʔə/

derivational suffix (verb → noun)

derives an abstract noun from a verb

Derived Terms

  • pa’a ぱあ thought
  • cura’a ゆらあ time
  • qacca’a げっやあ choice
  • qira’a ねらあ roughness

’ahatilaru

High Lulani

あはてわる

/ʔəˌhatʰɨˈlaɽʉ/

derived compound abstract noun

anniversary; birthday

Notes

usually used with dissu でっす to feel

Examples

ʔahatilaru dissunagi!

。あはてわるでっすなぎ。

’ahatilaru dissu-nagi

anniversary feel-fut;sta

“Happy birthday!”

Etymology

’ahati あはて happiness + laru わる year

’ala

High Lulani

あわ

/ˈʔalə/

inanimate mass noun

heat

Derived Terms

    • ’alamusa あわむさ sun’s heat
    • ’alaxuhha あわずっは heat of the fire
    • puci’ala ぷちあわ summer
    • naffi’ala なっべあわ spring
    • japa’ala ぢぱあわ haze
    • cussi’ala ゆっせあわ to feel hot

Notes

these are just about the only terms of this type. Anything else uses the genitive.

Examples

    daqa ’ala
  • だげ あわ
  • da-qa ’ala
  • water-gen heat
  • “the heat of the water”

count abstract noun

temperature degree

Notes

This temperature scale is set with 0 0 at absolute zero, and 844 444 at the triple point of water.

In ordinary use, temperatures between 788 477 and 1012 477 are given without the hundreds place.

Numbers in bold are in decimal, numbers in italics are in balanced sesquidecimal.

’anu

High Lulani

あぬ

/ˈʔanʉ/

intransitive

to be balanced

Examples

Kalupahi ’anu.

。かをぱひ あぬ。

kalu-pahi ’anu.

Body-1gen balance.

“I am healthy.”

mathematics

to equal

Examples

Kifi ju’i nuru ’anu salumi.

。きべ よい ぬる あぬ さをみ。

kifi ju’i nuru ’anu salumi.

Three add four equal seven.

“Three plus four is seven.”

See Also

  • ju’i よい plus
  • tali たえ subtract
  • batu ばと multiply
  • saki さき divide

-ba

See also: ba

High Lulani

ば

/bə/

derivational suffix (verb → noun)

derives an animate agentive noun from a verb

Examples

  • ’ussaba うっさば follower
  • caba やば helper
  • hisuba ひすば administrator

derivational suffix (number → inanimate noun)

polyhedron; polytope

Derived Terms

  • kifiba きべば tetrahedron
  • nuruba ぬるば cube
  • kifibara きべばら octahedron
  • guhiba ぐひば dodecahedron
  • takkiba たっきば icosahedron
  • pu’iba ぷいば sphere

bitta

High Lulani

びった

/ˈbitːə/

inanimate noun

time

Definition

the two temporal dimensions

Notes

The first dimension of time is subjective: a person’s birth is before their death.

The second dimension is objective: if one time-travels into the past, then one’s death may well be upstream of one’s birth.

Derived Terms

  • jannibitta ぢっにびった to time travel

Hypernyms

  • calu やを dimension

See Also

  • ’u’ili ういえ reality
  • sufi すべ space
  • maʔu まっう gingla

bunali

High Lulani

ぶなえ

/bʉˈnalɨ/

derived abstract noun

rhyme; assonance

Definition

to have the same vowels and placement of geminates

Examples

(These are perhaps nonsense words, to demonstrate bunali)

  • papa / para
  • kana / lara
  • biru / kitu
  • kippu / lirru

Non-examples

  • biru / baru - different vowel sound
  • kiru / kirru - different geminate placement

Etymology

buna ぶな homophone + -li え quasi-

だずにきべぎ・げさ

/dəˌɕunɨˈkʰifɨgiˈŋasə/

derived animate compound noun animal

coelacanth; three-tail fish

Etymology

  • daxuni だずに tail + kifi きべ three + gi ぎ to have
  • qasa げさ fish

Notes

Named for its three-lobed caudal fin

See Also

  • List of Animals

dissu

High Lulani

でっす

/ˈdisːʉ/

ambitransitive perceptive verb

to feel

Notes

Used for emotions and loves, often compounded. Such compounds tend to be adjectival verbs.

Examples

ʔusu sacu dissu ’ahati.

。うす さゆ でっす あはて。

1int 2abl feel happiness.

’usu sacu dissu ’ahati.

“You make me happy.”

Derived Terms

  • dissu’ahati でっすあはて to be happy
  • dissu’isili でっすいせえ to be sad
  • dissu’ulanu でっすうわぬ to be aroused
  • dissutihura でっすてほら to be astonished
  • dissumalliju でっすまっえよ to be happy
  • dissumici でっすみち to feel peace
  • diss·sutti でっすすって to be afraid
  • diss·samma でっすさっま to feel romantic

abstract noun

youth; newness

Derived Terms

    • dissuri でっすり stranger
    • diss·sa でっすさ young person
    • dissudanagi でっすだなぎ pardon
    • padissu ぱでっす to learn

dumi

High Lulani

どみ

/ˈdumɨ/

abstract noun ~ modal occasion adverb

nighttime hours; night; evening

Antonym

  • musa むさ daylight

abstract noun ~ purpose adverb

attempt; try to

Notes

Does not imply anything about success or failure.

When used with ablative promotion, gives nuance of encouraged.

Examples

Quhu kupaji dasikka mihu dumi.

。もほくぱじだせっかみほどみ。

quhu ku-paji dasi-kka mihu dumi.

3ani;tra dat-fruit eat-abv 3ani;int try.

“She encouraged him to eat fruit.”

/ˈhaɽʉ/

quasi-transitive intransitive symmetric verb

to accompany

Negative Complement

  • sa さ solitude

Examples

ʔa’ima haru sada.

。あいまはるさだ。

’a’ima haru sa-da.

Traveller accompany solitude-negative_aspect.

“The traveller is lonely.”

Derived Terms

  • harusa はるさ to be alone

adposition

with animates with

with inanimates consisting of

subordinating conjunction

at the same time; alongside; while; as

derived auxiliary

will quit; will stop doing; fut;hab<trm>

Etymology

hu fut;hab + -ar- 、あら、 trm

’i

See also: -’i

High Lulani

い

/ʔi/

ambitransitive communicative verb

to say; to speak; to tell

Negative Complement

sajja さっぢ silence

Derived Terms

    • ’isinna いせっな to tell a story
    • ’i’issi いいっせ to sing
    • ’ibibu いびぶ to complain
    • ’idajabi いだぢび to read aloud
    • ’idata いだた to reply
    • ’icipu いちぷ to ask
    • ’ikahu いかほ to grunt
    • ’igina いぎな to request
    • ’iqaca いげや to give one’s point of view
    • ’ilagi いわぎ to scream
    • ’iluxxa いをっざ to request
    • ’ifuhhanaku いふっはなく to agree
    • ’ihucu いほゆ to inform
    • daru’i だるい because
    • gufu’i ぐふい radio

Examples

ʔusu jusi ’i li lu’i fu ra’u.

。うす よせ い え をい ふ らう 。

’usu jusi ’i li fu ra’u.

1int 3ani;dat say com love 2tra prs;sta.

“I told her that I love you.”

ʔusu palu’i ’i.

。うす ぱをい い。

’usu pa-lu’i ’i.

1int towards-love speak.

“I talked about love.”

High Lulani

/mə/

clausal conjunction

where; when

Notes

most often used as a prefix for adverbial location clauses

。うすだせまあで、なら。

’usu dasi ma-’adi, nara.

1int eat where-near, sleep.

“I eat near where I sleep.”

nufira

High Lulani

ぬべら

/nʉfiɽə/

inanimate derived compound noun ~ modal adverb

want; desire; want to

Notes

When used adverbially, this word tends to only be used in first person, or second person questions.

Examples

ʔusu ra’u dihuri nufira.

。うすらうでほりぬべら。

ʔusu ra’u di-huri nufira.

1int prs;sta down-sea want.

“I want to be under the sea.”

Etymology

nu ぬ desire + fira べら wish

-qa

See also: qa

High Lulani

げ

/ŋə/

derivational suffix (numeral, verb, pronoun → noun)

nominaliser; nmn

Definition

Denotes a specific case of a general number or pronoun.

Examples

    • paguqa ぱぐげ mine
    • baqa ばげ yours
    • disiqa でせげ theirs
    • raqa らげ the two of them

qacca

High Lulani

げっや

/ˈŋacːə/

ambitransitive perceptive verb

choose; decide; prefer; rather

Derived Terms

  • qacca’a げっやあ choice

Examples

ʔusu qacca ’iti.

。うす げっや いて。

’usu qacca ’iti.

1int choose milk.

lit. “I choose milk.”

“I’ll have the milk.”

ʔusu ku’iti qacca.

。うす くいて げっや。

’usu ku-’iti qacca.

1int dat-milk choose

lit. “I choose towards milk.”

“I prefer milk.”

    tali

    High Lulani

    たえ

    /ˈtʰalɨ/

    mathematics particle

    subtract; minus

    Examples

    Qihha tali bila ’anu kifi.

    。ねっは たえ びわ あぬ きべ。

    qihha tali bila ’anu kifi.

    Zero take ree equal three.

    “Zero subtract minus three equals three.”

    See Also

    • ’anu あぬ equal
    • ju’i よい plus
    • batu ばと multiply
    • saki さき divide

    transitive motive dative verb

    Examples

    ʔaggami pi kalutuhhisa tali

    ’ita’i.

    。あっがみ ぴ かをとっひさ たえ いたい。

    ’aggami pi kalu-tuhhisa tali ’ita’i.

    Police_officer pst;sta abl-farmer take car.

    “The police officer took the car from the farmer.”

    tana

    High Lulani

    たな

    /ˈtʰanə/

    abstract noun

    there is; what there is

    Examples

    Tana ru lulani.

    。たな る をわに。

    tana ru lulani.

    there_is prs;gno queen.

    “There is a queen (in existence).”

    Notes

    while this is not a noun in the strict sense of the word, it does act like one when used by itself as a subject. This noun can be used as the base to nominalise adpositions.

    Examples

    • tanadi たなで what is above
    • tanajimuli たなじむえ what is outside

    See Also

    • malu まを there is

    /ɕu/

    transitive apparent verb

    to put out; to radiate; to broadcast

    Notes

    Inanimate themes are objects, animate themes use ka

    Examples

    Filli pixi xusina.

    。べっえ ぴし ずせな。

    filli pixi xu-sina.

    2int 1dat seem-beauty.

    “I think you’re pretty.”

    Filli ka’aggami xu.

    。べっえ かあっがみず。

    filli ka-’aggami xu.

    2int as-policeman.

    “You look like a policeman.”
